e GUI A GUI determines the look and feel' of a system the shape of windows buttons and scroll bars how you resize things how you edit files The OPEN LOOK GUI is specified developed and maintained jointly by Sun Microsystems and AT T or USL See Also Bibliography What is OpenWindows OpenWindows is a windowing environment that conforms to the OPEN LOOK Graphical User Interface It's compatible with the window system from MIT as well as currently Sun's NeWS and SunView so you can intermix programs written for any of those It comes from Sun and also with System V Release from certain OpenWindows is sometimes also called openwin or xnews after the program used to start it and the main executable itself It should not be called Windows' or 'OPEN LOOK' or OpenLook' as these terms are either wrong or apply to something A commerical OpenWindows source licence costs about for the server plus about for DeskSet and another for The current versions of OpenWindows for various platforms are SunOS on Sun Solaris SunOS on SPARC Solaris SunOS on SPARC See Also Mixing and OpenWindows Where can I get it What are OLIT XView and TNT These are all toolkits for programmers to use in developing programs that conform to the OPEN LOOK See the Bibliography for documentation on the individual Here's a brief summary OLIT was AT T's OPEN LOOK Intrinsics Toolkit for the X Window system it used a widget set and was probably the easiest for people who were already Xt programmers to You could buy the source from AT T although you didn't get the same version tht Sun Sun includes the OLIT library in OpenWindows it is also often included in System V Release It was written in The release of OLIT in OpenWindows was OLIT OLIT support passed to USL then a division of AT T now owned by Novell who replaced it with MoOLIT Note that because of the nature of Xt subclassing you will probably want or need OLIT source in order to develop a large application or anything else that uses see the proceedings of the X Technical Conference XView is Sun's toolkit for written in XView is similar in programmer interface to There's even a shell script to help migrate source code from SunView to XView is often said to be the easiest toolkit to learn if you are not familiar with X The XView toolkit is included in OpenWindows and full source is available by anonymous ftp from and elsewhere The current version of XView from Sun is Despite rumours to the contrary some even from within Sun the XView toolkit is NOT about to be dropped by XView will be included in the next release of OpenWindows unlike On the other hand the XView toolkit is not likely to receive as much attention from Sun in the future as The NeWS Toolkit TNT was an object oriented programming system based on the PostScript language and TNT implements many of the OPEN LOOK interface components required to build the user interface of an It's currently included in The current version of TNT from Sun is Release contains some incompatibilities with tNt' and TNT but Sun are committed to supporting the API at least until they stop NeWS support some time later this year and replace it with Display You might ask what is committed to' means in this context the answer seems to be that it means absolutely Sun currently asserts that it is committed to OLIT The C User Interface Toolkit UIT consists of an object oriented C class library layered on top of XView and a tool to generate code from DevGuide GIL The UIT also includes features that simplify event management and the use of PostScript and It is said to be compatible with OpenWindows and and presumably since the release mentions that it works on Solaris UIT is not an official Sun supported product but an ongoing project of various people within It can be found on in the MIT contrib directory as use binary mode Where does Motif fit in It doesn't Motif is an alternative Graphical User Interface that is being developed by It has a look and feel' reminiscent of Microsoft Windows and the OS Presentation There are no non commercial Motif toolkits available although the Motif source is sold reasonably cheaply by Although Motif is currently available on more platforms than OpenWindows the OPEN LOOK GUI is almost certainly used on many more machines simply because Sun and have such a large installed Sun's CD WARE Volume contains a roadmap for improving Motif applications by converting them to OLIT there are also notes in the Periodic Table' OLIT demo OPENWINHOME demo What is MoOLIT MoOLIT is a version of OLIT from AT T USL that lets users choose between a Motif and an OPEN LOOK UI feel at run It will be part of System V Release Contact Joanne Newbauer What about that Display PostScript thing Sun and Adobe have agreed that Sun will include the DPS extension to X in the next release of DPS is essentially a badly designed hack on top of a slow Level PostScript interpreter intended to give a very small subset of the functionality of NeWS whilst simultaneously being harder to use as I understand The only real advantage it has over NeWS is that the manual is much smaller being generally less complete DPS is also available on more kinds of Performance on our RS is not suitable for interactive work what it will be like on the SPARCStation remains to be Note that whereas X NeWS fonts are shared by both subsystems the DPS extension to X does not make Type PostScript fonts available to ordinary It is not like ATM on a PC in this there is at least one third party version which does make fonts available however Subject Window Managers olwm olvwm What are olwm and olvwm They are window A window manager is the part of the X Window system that is responsible for deciding how to lay out windows on the screen and for managing the user's interaction with the Olwm is the standard OPEN LOOK window It's included with all of the OpenWindows implementations and you can also get the source by ftp since Sun donated Olvwm is a version of olwm that manages a virtual desktop' hence the v' in its name It shows a little map on the screen with the currently displayed area represented by a little You can move around by dragging the rectangle or with the arrow This lets you run several clients applications and move the display around from one to the Olvwm was derived from the OpenWindows olwm by Scott Oaks you need to have XView to compile Get olvwm from an ftp site such as in the contrib directory there are three patches Can I use my favorite window manager with OpenWindows instead of olwm If you use twm for example or mwm you won't be able to use the Pin and Unpin feature of olwm and you probably won't see the footers some windows use to display certain If you use twm you'll want to use the function to unpin menus and get rid of programs that don't have a quit' button when not run under For twm put this in your HOME LeftTitleButton target where target is a icon from usr include Alternatively try Add a menu to each window managed by twm or tvtwm LeftTitleButton menu menu Quit For mwm you can double click on the menu icon on the left of the title bar to dismiss a pop up window I am told See the manual page for your window manager twm etc Subject OpenWindows Terminals and Other Displays Can I use olwm and olvwm without OpenWindows or on an X Terminal The OpenWindows xnews server combines SunView NeWS PostScript and This means that it can run programs compiled for any of those Unfortunately it means that some OpenWindows programs need either NeWS or SunView support and thus won't run on an X This includes pageview in You can use olwm or olvwm see above on an X terminal or a non Open Windows display and most OPEN LOOK clients OLIT or XView ones will work perfectly You may find that you get complaints about fonts not being If so see the Fonts section If you are running the window manager built in to an NCD terminal you may have problems with input focus setting Input True in the terminal's XDefault file in usr lib xdm may or may not Subject Configuration F